<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900723-0056</DOCNO><DOCID>900723-0056.</DOCID><HL>   Politics andamp; Policy:   Bush Plans Daily Sessions   On Deficit-Cutting Effort</HL><DATE>07/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- President Bush is inviting congressionalleaders to meet with him daily to speed progress toward adeficit-reduction compromise.   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole said yesterday onNBC-TV's &quot;Meet the Press&quot; that Mr. Bush plans to begin thesessions tomorrow.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;You're going to see a more active President Bush,&quot; saidthe Kansas senator, who spoke to Mr. Bush over the weekend. AWhite House spokesman later confirmed the invitation butcouldn't say whether the meetings would continue beyond thisweek.   Democrats have been clamoring for Mr. Bush to take a moreprominent role in the talks between administration officialsand a bipartisan contingent of 21 members of Congress. Thetalks began in mid-May.   Unless the pace picks up considerably, negotiators areunlikely to meet their stated goal of reaching an agreementin the next two or three weeks. Budget Director RichardDarman has argued that a breakthrough will occur only in asmaller group.   Sen. Dole's aides said Mr. Bush's daily meetings willinclude Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell (D., Maine),House Speaker Thomas Foley (D., Wash.), House Majority LeaderDick Gephardt (D., Mo.), House Minority Leader Bob Michel(R., Ill.) and Sen. Dole.</TEXT></DOC>